<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="5f46a5f0-b5bd-566a-85d0-4aba3346bdd3" activityNameId="582c2bf5-99ce-5040-b8d3-b0667eaaece5" parentActivityId="f2179300-eada-46a0-8c45-ebdd21c79eff" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">phenol production, cumene oxidation</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Hock process</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> Cumene process</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en"> cumene-phenol process</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the co-production of phenol and acetone by means of cumene oxidation. This process, also called Hock process, transforms cumene and oxygen into phenol and acetone.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">phenol is an organic substance with a CAS no. : 000108-95-2. It is called 'phenol' under IUPAC naming and its molecular formula is: C6H6O. It is solid under normal conditions of temperature and pressure, has a crystalline form and has an odour characteristic of aromatic compounds. It is modelled as a pure substance. Modelling this substance in a solution requires the user to add the solvent of their choice in their models. There is no publicly available information about the consumption of this substance on a consumer level. On industrial sites, the substance is used for the manufacture of products in the following sectors: coating products, fillers, putties, plasters, modelling clay, inks and toners and polymers.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">acetone is an organic substance with a CAS no. : 000067-64-1. It is called 'propan-2-one' under IUPAC naming and its molecular formula is: C3H6O. It is liquid under normal conditions of temperature and pressure. It is modelled as a pure substance. Modelling this substance in a solution requires the user to add the solvent of their choice in their models. On a consumer level, is used in the following products: coating products, anti-freeze products, lubricants and greases, adhesives and sealants, fillers, putties, plasters, modelling clay and non-metal-surface treatment products. On industrial sites, the substance is used for the manufacture of products in the following sectors: washing &amp; cleaning products, laboratory chemicals, photo-chemicals, cosmetics and personal care products and pharmaceuticals.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In western Europe the production capacity of phenol amounted to 2.6 million tonnes in 2014, which was equivalent to 21% of the global production. Notably, the economic viability of the phenol production,via the Hook process, is strongly linked to the price of the acetone by.product that is characterised by high variability.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Weber M., Weber M., Kleine-Boymann M. (2011): Phenol, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Gallardo Hipolito, M. 2011. Life Cycle Assessment of platform chemicals from fossil and lignocellulosic biomass scenarios LCA of phenolic compounds, solvent, soft and hard plastic precursors. Master in Industrial Ecology. Norwegian University of Science and Technology Department of Energy and Process Engineering. Retrieved from: http://daim.idi.ntnu.no/masteroppgaver/006/6362/tittelside.pdf, accessed 6 January 2017</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Saygin, D. 2009. Chemical and Petrochemical Sector Potential of best practice technology and other measures for improving energy efficiency. IEA information paper. IEA/OECD. Retrieved from: https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/chemical_petrochemical_sector.pdf, accessed 6 January 2017</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Falcke, Heino, et al. "Best Available Techniques (BAT) reference document for the production of large volume organic chemicals." Publications Office of the European Union: Luxembourg (2017).</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">In the Hock process, cumene reacts with oxygen to give phenol and acetone. For each kilogram of phenol produced, 0.62 kg of acetone are obtained. The process consists of two fundamental chemical reactions: cumene oxidation with oxygen to cumene hydroperoxide (CHP). CHP is then cleaved to phenol and acetone by using a strong mineral acid or zeolite-based catalyst.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Chemical reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">C9H12 + R°-&gt; C9H12° C9H12° + O2 -&gt;C6H6O + C3H6O</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">The oxidation of cumene is usually carried out in a series of bubble column reactors. Fresh as well as recycled cumene are fed to the first reactor with oxygen acting as an oxidant in each reactor. The bubble columns are operated at pressures ranging from atmospheric to about 700 kPa and temperatures in the range 80 –120 °C. The temperature can be controled by internal or external heat exchangers. The condensed cumene is recycled to the oxidation reactors. The CHP concentration in the oxidation product is increased by vacuum distillation in column to about 65-90 %. In a second step, the formed CHP is cleaved to phenol and acetone. For this, a series of heat exchangers within a circulation loop are used as reactors because the reaction is very fast and exothermic. The CHP is spontaneously diluted in the circulation product, which consists of phenol, acetone, cumene, and several byproducts as well as residual amounts of CHP. Normally sulfuric acid is used as the catalyst at a concentration of several hundred parts per million by weight. The temperature is in the range 40 – 80 °C at atmospheric pressure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, a yield of 95% was assumed.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reference(s):</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chauvel, Alain, Gilles Lefebvre, and L. Castex in "Petrochemical processes. Technical and economical characteristics Vol. 2." (1989).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Weber M., Weber M., Kleine-Boymann M. (2011): Phenol, Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry, Wiley-VCH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59–67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9">Gallardo Hipolito, M. 2011. Life Cycle Assessment of platform chemicals from fossil and lignocellulosic biomass scenarios LCA of phenolic compounds, solvent, soft and hard plastic precursors. Master in Industrial Ecology. Norwegian University of Science and Technology Department of Energy and Process Engineering. Retrieved from: http://daim.idi.ntnu.no/masteroppgaver/006/6362/tittelside.pdf, accessed 6 January 2017</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10">Saygin, D. 2009. Chemical and Petrochemical Sector Potential of best practice technology and other measures for improving energy efficiency. IEA information paper. IEA/OECD. Retrieved from: https://www.iea.org/publications/freepublications/publication/chemical_petrochemical_sector.pdf, accessed 6 January 2017</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Falcke, H., Holbrook, S., Clenahan, I., Carretero, A.L., Sanalan, T., Brinkmann, T., Joze, R., Benoît, Z., Serge, R. and Sancho, L.D., 2017. Best Available Techniques (BAT) reference document for the production of large volume organic chemicals. Publications Office of the European Union: Luxembourg</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2017-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2017) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015-2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of  tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2462760. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Falcke, Heino, et al. "Best Available Techniques (BAT) reference document for the production of large volume organic chemicals." Publications Office of the European Union: Luxembourg (2017).</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
